+## Document Pros and Cons
+
+When a plan picks between alternatives (library, architecture pattern, data structure, approach), include a brief pros/cons/why block:
+
+> **Pros:** [advantages]
+> **Cons:** [disadvantages]
+> **Why we chose this:** [reasoning]
+
+Proportional to decision weight — a minor choice gets one line each, a major choice gets a paragraph. If one option clearly dominates, auto-select and state why.
+
+## Prose Quality
+
+All non-code text in the plan (descriptions, context, rationale) must read like it was written by a human engineer. Avoid AI-isms:
+
+- leverages, delves, ensures, facilitates, robust, seamless, comprehensive, streamlined
+- "This elegant solution" / "This powerful feature"
+- Filler hedging: "It's worth noting that", "It should be mentioned that"
+
+Write plainly. Say what it does, why, and move on.
+
 ## Remember
 - Exact file paths always
-- Complete code in every step — if a step changes code, show the code
+- Complete code in the plan — every function, type, and constant must appear in full somewhere. Later steps may reference earlier-defined code by name instead of repeating it.
 - Exact commands with expected output
